{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":5606,"record_hash":"sha256:eab7115d25677ed1464474b2fb1be95a7db27d92aff9ed539992a9c3dd18ac21","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:36:35.827Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 98cf01\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 627\nOutput:\n\nThe cautious default is derived propagation. It avoids making the session claim\ntoo much, while still allowing branch/PR views to show relevant sessions.\n\nPersisted propagation is not part of v1 automatic scoring. If explicit\nrelationships are added later through an API or product flow, they should mean\n\"this session is relevant to this target\", not \"this session generated this\ntarget.\"\n\nGitButler's multiple-branches-in-one-worktree model is the main argument for\nturn-scoped precision. A single agent session can mostly build one feature\nbranch while a specific turn produces a bugfix that the user sends to another\nbranch. Whole-session association is therefore useful but not always precise\nenough for review sharing.\n\nRecommended shape:\n\n- store sessions as the durable transcript object\n- start with derived read-time association results from capture turn evidence\n- let capture turn evidence highlight or filter the relevant part of the session\n- keep existing explicit target-to-session links as stronger evidence if they\n  already exist\n- allow future relationship metadata to carry optional turn scope if an explicit\n  API/product flow needs durable links\n\nIn other words, capture turn scope should refine a session relationship. It\nshould not move transcript ownership onto branches, changes, commits, or pull\nrequests.\n\n## Persist Or Recompute\n\nThe capture turn layer could be stored directly, or some of it could be\nrecomputed from existing records and Git state.\n\nReasons to persist capture turns:\n\n- preserves exact capture boundaries\n- preserves repository state at the time of capture\n- supports later association even after branches or worktree state changed\n- makes handoff and review timelines cheaper to query\n\nReasons to recompute some association:\n\n- avoids prematurely committing to a wrong relationship\n- keeps durable metadata smaller\n- allows better algorithms later without rewriting old data\n\nMy current take: persist the observation, not the conclusion. Store capture turn\nobjects and environment snapshots. Use them to compute association results at\nread time. Persist relationships only if an explicit API/product flow later\nneeds durable links.\n\n## Access Patterns\n\nThe model should make these reads efficient.\n\nDefine the read surface around the two product use cases:\n\n- `listSessions(project, filters, cursor)`: discovers sessions for handoff\n- `getSessionTimeline(session_key, window?)`: returns turn summaries plus\n  hydrated records for a bounded handoff window\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:36:35.827Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}